<magic_link_security_guide>
<title>MAGIC LINK SECURITY (Passwordless Authentication)</title>

<critical>Magic links enable passwordless authentication but introduce unique security risks. Focus on link expiration, token reuse, email client prefetching, token entropy, account enumeration, and referrer leakage. Weak implementation enables account takeover without credentials.</critical>

<scope>
- Link expiration testing (time-based, use-based)
- Token reuse after successful login
- Email client link prefetching issues
- Token entropy and predictability analysis
- Account enumeration via magic link flow
- Link hijacking via referrer/redirect leakage
- Concurrent link generation
- Token in URL vs body
- Rate limiting bypass
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Request magic link for test account
2. Analyze token: length, entropy, predictability
3. Test expiration: time-based (minutes/hours), use-based (single/multi-use)
4. Test reuse: use same link multiple times
5. Test prefetch: check server logs for automated requests
6. Test enumeration: timing/response differences for valid vs invalid emails
7. Test hijacking: referrer leakage, HTTP downgrade
8. Test concurrent: generate multiple links, verify oldest invalidated
9. Test rate limits: request many links rapidly
</methodology>

<token_reuse>
<multi_use_tokens>
- Token valid for multiple logins
- Attacker with old link can login anytime
- No single-use enforcement

Test:
1. Request magic link
2. Click link → successful login (session 1)
3. Logout or clear session
4. Click same link again → successful login (session 2)
5. If succeeds: token reusable
</multi_use_tokens>

<no_invalidation_after_use>
- Token not invalidated after successful authentication
- Link remains valid until expiration
- Forwarded email enables repeated access

Impact:
- Email forwarded to support → support can login as user
- Email cached by email gateway → accessible later
- Attacker with email access can login repeatedly
</no_invalidation_after_use>

<no_invalidation_after_password_set>
- User sets password after magic link login
- Old magic links still valid
- Password doesn't invalidate passwordless access

Test:
1. Login via magic link
2. Set password in account settings
3. Logout
4. Use old magic link → still works
</no_invalidation_after_password_set>
</token_reuse>

<expiration_issues>
<no_time_expiration>
- Magic link never expires
- Valid indefinitely
- Compromised email → permanent account access

Test:
1. Request magic link
2. Wait 24-72 hours
3. Click link → if works: no expiration
</no_time_expiration>

<long_expiration>
- Expiration too long (24+ hours)
- OWASP recommends 10-15 minutes max
- Increases window for link theft

Check email:
"This link expires in 24 hours" → too long
</long_expiration>

<no_use_based_expiration>
- Link valid for time period, can be used multiple times
- Should be single-use or very short-lived
</no_use_based_expiration>
</expiration_issues>

<email_client_prefetching>
<automatic_link_clicking>
- Email clients (Outlook Safe Links, Gmail) prefetch URLs
- Server sees request before user clicks
- Token consumed by prefetch, user's click fails

Example:
1. User receives magic link
2. Email client prefetches link (checks for malware)
3. Server processes prefetch as login, creates session
4. User clicks link → token already used, login fails

Detection:
- Check User-Agent for email security scanners:
  - Microsoft Office Existence Discovery
  - GoogleImageProxy
  - Mimecast
- Check for rapid requests (prefetch + user click)
</automatic_link_clicking>

<session_hijacking_via_prefetch>
- Prefetch creates session
- Session ID leaked in response
- Attacker monitors network, steals session

Mitigation:
- Don't create session on GET request
- Require POST with token for actual login
- Use CSRF token in addition to magic link token
</session_hijacking_via_prefetch>
</email_client_prefetching>

<token_entropy>
<weak_tokens>
- Predictable patterns: sequential, timestamp-based
- Low entropy: short tokens, limited character set
- Example weak: MD5(email + timestamp)

Analysis:
1. Request 10+ magic links
2. Analyze tokens: length, pattern, character set
3. Calculate entropy: bits = length × log2(charset_size)
4. Minimum: 128 bits recommended

Example:
token=abc123 (6 chars, 36^6 ≈ 41 bits, WEAK)
token=7f8e3a9c1b2d4e6f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b (32 hex = 128 bits, OK)
</weak_tokens>

<token_prediction>
- UUID v1: contains timestamp and MAC address (predictable)
- Sequential: easy to guess next token
- Hash of email: attacker knows email, can generate token

Test:
1. Generate multiple tokens for same/different emails
2. Look for patterns
3. Try to predict next token
4. Test prediction with new magic link request
</token_prediction>
</token_entropy>

<account_enumeration>
<timing_attacks>
- Valid email: generate token, send email (slower)
- Invalid email: immediate rejection (faster)

Test:
valid_time = measure_time('/magic-link', {'email': 'exists@example.com'})
invalid_time = measure_time('/magic-link', {'email': 'notexist@example.com'})
if valid_time > invalid_time + 100ms:
    print("Timing-based enumeration possible")
</timing_attacks>

<response_differences>
- Status code: 200 for valid, 404 for invalid
- Message: "Link sent" vs "Email not found"
- Different response structure/headers

Generic response still leaks via timing
</response_differences>

<email_delivery_side_channel>
- Monitor email server logs
- SMTP connection for valid email
- No connection for invalid
</email_delivery_side_channel>
</account_enumeration>

<link_hijacking>
<referrer_leakage>
- User clicks magic link
- User navigates to external site
- Referrer header contains token

Example:
Magic link: https://example.com/auth?token=SECRET123
User navigates away, browser sends:
Referer: https://example.com/auth?token=SECRET123

Attacker's site logs referrer → steals token
</referrer_leakage>

<http_downgrade>
- Magic link uses HTTP not HTTPS
- Token transmitted in plaintext
- MITM can intercept

Check email:
http://example.com/auth?token=SECRET (VULNERABLE)
vs
https://example.com/auth?token=SECRET (OK, but still in URL)
</http_downgrade>

<token_in_url>
- Token in URL query parameter
- Logged in server access logs, proxy logs
- Visible in browser history
- Leaked via Referrer header

Better: use POST with token in body
Or: token in URL fragment (#) not sent to server
</token_in_url>

<open_redirect>
- Magic link has redirect parameter
- Attacker adds ?redirect=http://evil.com
- User clicks, logs in, redirected to attacker
- Session cookie sent to attacker (if not SameSite)

Test:
https://example.com/auth?token=VALID&redirect=http://attacker.com
</open_redirect>
</link_hijacking>

<concurrent_link_generation>
<multiple_valid_links>
- Generate multiple magic links for same email
- All links remain valid simultaneously
- Increases attack surface

Test:
1. Request magic link → get token1
2. Request again → get token2
3. Request again → get token3
4. Test all tokens → all work
5. Should: only latest token valid, previous invalidated
</multiple_valid_links>

<no_invalidation_on_new_request>
- Requesting new link doesn't invalidate old ones
- User can have 10+ valid links active
- Forwarded/leaked old links still work
</no_invalidation_on_new_request>
</concurrent_link_generation>

<rate_limiting>
<unlimited_link_generation>
- No limit on magic link requests
- Attacker floods user email
- Email DoS attack

Test:
for i in range(1000):
    POST /magic-link {'email': 'victim@example.com'}
// If all succeed: no rate limit
</unlimited_link_generation>

<bypass_techniques>
- IP rotation
- X-Forwarded-For spoofing
- Email case variation: Victim@example.com
- Email comment: victim+1@example.com
</bypass_techniques>
</rate_limiting>

<session_handling>
<session_before_verification>
- Session created on link click (GET)
- Before token validated
- Attacker can fixate session

Test:
1. Click magic link
2. Intercept before token validation
3. Capture session cookie
4. Token validates, session authenticated
5. Use captured session → authenticated
</session_before_verification>

<session_not_tied_to_token>
- Any session can use magic link
- Session from different browser/device works
- Enables session fixation attacks
</session_not_tied_to_token>
</session_handling>

<validation>
1. Request magic link, capture token from email
2. Test reuse: use token multiple times, verify invalidated after first use
3. Test expiration: wait increasing time intervals, verify expiry ~10-15 minutes
4. Test entropy: collect multiple tokens, analyze for patterns/predictability
5. Test enumeration: compare timing/responses for valid vs invalid emails
6. Test hijacking: check for referrer leakage, HTTP usage, token in URL
7. Test concurrent: generate multiple links, verify older ones invalidated
8. Test rate limiting: request many links rapidly
9. Demonstrate impact: successful account access with stolen/reused token
</validation>

<false_positives>
- High-entropy tokens (128+ bits)
- Single-use, short expiration (10-15 minutes)
- Generic responses hiding enumeration
- HTTPS with token in POST body
- Proper rate limiting (max 3-5 requests per hour per email)
- Older links invalidated on new request
</false_positives>

<impact>
- Account takeover via stolen/leaked link
- Persistent access via reusable tokens
- Email flooding DoS
- Account enumeration (user database mapping)
- Session hijacking via prefetch
- Link forwarding enables unauthorized access
</impact>

<pro_tips>
1. Check email headers for magic link—view raw source
2. Test token format: JWT, UUID, random string
3. Always test reuse—most common vulnerability
4. Measure response times with median of 10+ requests
5. Check server logs for prefetch requests (email security scanners)
6. Test on mobile apps—may have different implementation
7. Token in URL is immediate red flag—should be POST body
8. Test after password set—old links should be invalidated
9. Check for redirect parameter—open redirect vector
10. Test "suspicious activity" limits—may block link generation
11. Verify link works only from recipient's IP/browser (rare but good security)
12. Check if link can be used from email forwarding (should be prevented)
</pro_tips>

<remember>Secure magic links require: high-entropy tokens, single-use, short expiration (10-15 minutes), rate limiting, generic responses, HTTPS with POST, no referrer leakage, and invalidation on new request. Token in URL is vulnerable to logs, history, and referrer leakage. Always prefer POST-based authentication over GET.</remember>
</magic_link_security_guide>
